● Looked through the README, CLI flags, TAP output, and existing keyboard/watcher infra. Here are the ones I'd argue clear the "significant UX win" bar — ranked by how much they actually change the day-to-day:

  1. --failed / persistent failure cache

  The single biggest TDD friction left. After a failing run your next move is almost always "rerun that one." Today you have to copy the path out of the TAP output (and there's no
  way to scope down further than a file). Stash the failures from the last run in tmp/.qunitx-last-failures.json — { file, moduleId, testName, browser } — and let qunitx
  --only-failed (-f) re-run just those. Pairs perfectly with the daemon and watch mode. Vitest/Jest/pytest all ship this; not having it is the most conspicuous gap.

  2. -t / --filter test-name pattern . -t ok, maybe -m as well?

  No way to narrow within a file right now. A 30-test file = run all 30. Every neighboring runner has it: Jest -t, Vitest -t, Mocha --grep, AVA --match. QUnit already exposes
  QUnit.config.testFilter and moduleFilter (regex-capable), so this is mostly wiring. Combines naturally with #1 and the watch hotkeys below.

  3. Watch-mode interactive hotkeys (Vitest-style)

  The infrastructure exists (lib/setup/keyboard-events.ts, lib/utils/listen-to-keyboard-key.ts, ~100 LOC total) — only the bindings are missing. f = only failed, t = prompt for
  test-name regex, p = prompt for file glob, a = all, o = open output, q = quit. Turns --watch from "rerun on save" into an interactive REPL for the suite. Highest ratio of
  impact-to-implementation-cost on the list.

  4. Built-in code coverage (--coverage)

  The genuinely differentiating one. qunitx already drives Chrome over CDP — precise V8 coverage is one Profiler.startPreciseCoverage call plus takePreciseCoverage at run end,
  mapped through the existing source-map decoder. Default: terminal summary; optional --coverage=lcov,html. jsdom-based runners can't match real-browser coverage cleanly, and
  Playwright/Cypress coverage is awkward. This is the kind of feature that becomes a reason to choose qunitx over the alternative.

  5. --reporter=junit (small reporter slot, not a plugin system)

  Not glamorous, but JUnit XML is the format every enterprise CI dashboard ingests natively (GitHub Actions test summary, GitLab MR view, CircleCI Insights, BuildKite, Jenkins).
  Without it, adoption hits a wall in CI orgs that don't speak TAP. Mechanical to add — open a write stream, accumulate <testcase> per testEnd, flush on runEnd.




